<subsection xml:id="subsec-Using_RInstat_Running_a_hypothesis_test">
  <title>Using R-Instat: Running a hypothesis test</title>
  <p>
    The steps below walk through the process using a real example  testing whether pay significantly predicts hours worked.
  </p>
  <p>
    To run a hypothesis test in R-Instat:
  </p>
  <p> 
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\textbf{Step 1: Open the Appropriate Dialog}</m>
          <p>
            Navigate to <em>Model</em> <m>\rightarrow</m> <em>Fit Models</em> and choose the model
            that matches your data:
          </p>
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\text{One Variable Fit Model}</m> - this is used when analysing a single variable
                (example: testing if the mean hours worked equals a specific value).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
                <m>\text{Two Variable Fit Model}</m> - this is used when examining the relationship between
                two variables, such as whether pay predicts hours.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\text{Hypothesis Tests}</m> - this gives direct access to specific statistical tests
                without fitting a full model.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\textbf{Step 2: Select the Variables}</m>
          <p>
            In the Two Variable Fit Model dialog
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\text{Response Variable:}</m> <m>\textbf{hours}</m> this is the outcome you are trying to explain.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\text{Explanatory Variable:}</m> <m>\textbf{pay}</m> this is the predictor you believe
                influences hours.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\text{Distribution:}</m> Normal, this is appropriate because <m>\textbf{hours}</m> is a
                continuous, roughly symmetric variable.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            The Model Preview confirmed the formula:
            <me>
              \texttt{hours} \sim \texttt{pay}
            </me>
          </p>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="Two_Variable_Fit_Model_dialog">
          <caption>Two Variable Fit Model in R-Instat used for comparing two variables or testing relationships.</caption>
          <image source="images/Two-Variable-Fit-Model-in-R-Instat-used-for-comparing-hours-and-pay.png"/>
        </figure>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\textbf{Step 3: Choose the Test}</m>
          <p>
            R-Instat automatically runs a linear regression t-test on each coefficient
            when using the Two Variable Fit Model with a Normal distribution. This tests whether
            each predictor has a statistically significant relationship with the response variable.
          </p>
          <p>
            there are also other available tests in R-Instat
          </p>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\textbf{Step 4: Specify the Null Hypothesis and Confidence Level}</m>
          <p>
            For the <m>\texttt{hours} \sim \texttt{pay}</m> model, the hypotheses being tested are:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\text{Null Hypothesis (<m>H_0</m>):}</m> Pay has no effect on hours worked
                (slope <m>= 0</m>).
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\text{Alternative Hypothesis (<m>H_1</m>):}</m> Pay does have a significant
                effect on hours worked (slope <m>\neq 0</m>).
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\text{Confidence Level:}</m> 95% (the standard default, equivalent to
                <m>\alpha = 0.05</m>).
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\textbf{Step 5: Click OK — Reading the Output}</m>
        </p>
        <p>  
          After clicking OK, the Output Window displayed the following results.
          
          <figure xml:id="Two-Variable-Fit-Model-in-R-Instat-used-for-comparing-hours-and-pay-output1">
            <caption></caption>
            <image source="images/Two-Variable-Fit-Model-in-R-Instat-used-for-comparing-hours-and-pay-output1.png"/>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="Two-Variable-Fit-Model-in-R-Instat-used-for-comparing-hours-and-pay-output2">
            <caption></caption>
            <image source="images/Two-Variable-Fit-Model-in-R-Instat-used-for-comparing-hours-and-pay-output2.png"/>
          </figure>
        </p>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                The Model Equation
                <p>
                  <me>
                    \texttt{hours} = 2.4951 + 0.0975 \times \texttt{pay}
                  </me>
                  This means for every 1 unit increase in pay, hours worked is predicted to increase
                  by <m>0.0975</m> hours.
                </p>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Coefficients Table
                <p>
                  The <m>t</m>-value of <m>8.03</m> for <m>\textbf{pay}</m> is large, indicating a strong
                  effect. The <m>p</m>-value of <m>2.3 \times 10^{-10}</m> is far below <m>0.05</m>,
                  meaning the result is highly statistically significant.
                </p>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Model Fit Statistics
                <p>
                  The <m>\text{Residual Standard Error}</m> is <m>1.19</m>, meaning the average
                  prediction error is approximately <m>1.19</m> hours — reasonably small given the
                  scale of the data.
                </p>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Decision: Reject or Retain the Null Hypothesis?
                <p>
                  Since the <m>p</m>-value (<m>2.3 \times 10^{-10}</m>) is much less than <m>0.05</m>,
                  we <m>\text{reject the null hypothesis}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  There is strong statistical evidence that pay significantly predicts hours worked.
                  The relationship is positive: workers with higher pay tend to work more hours.
                </p>
              </p>
              <p>
                This example demonstrates how R-Instat makes hypothesis testing accessible by
                guiding users through variable selection, model setup, and automatic output
                interpretation all without writing R code manually.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
